ent-body"><p><span>One of my assumptions about the partisan divide in the c=
ountry follows quite a bit along what you said w.r.t. blue-collar voters, a=
nd it goes back to some pretty basic philosophy: am I who I am primarily ba=
sed on my (verbal, propositional) thoughts, or am I who I am based on how I=
 feel. And it seems to me that the educational (and media/progressive) elit=
e has become fairly detached from reality where hard-to-express (pre-verbal=
) experiences about the world come into play. Similar to Thomas Sowell's ar=
gument about the Anointed, the left-progressive worldview is based on abstr=
act and idealized rules about the (human and social) world, and each time w=
hen some basic feelings (borders matter, and fetuses are potential humans i=
n the making, who need protections, etc.) collide with that worldview, the =
verbally high-intelligent and educated people have a tendency of wanting to=
 override those feelings (of the unwashed masses) with some propositionally=
 justifiable (but fairly dogmatic) belief system, which in the end always t=
urns out to be a house of cards. Trump, on the other hand, firmly comes fro=
m a "shooting from the emotional hip" place. He reads the cultural room and=
 moment, and then promulgates a position that speaks to how people feel, de=
ep down, about issues. As a salesman, he is really, really good at that, an=
d because he speaks to A LOT of people's unspoken (and hard to talk about i=
n polite society) feelings, his support (in polling and elsewhere) is proba=
bly often underestimated, because when you ask people why they vote for Tru=
mp, it comes out (in the ears of the propositionally high minded, anyway) a=
s some version of "because!"</span></p><div role=3D"button" class=3D"show-a=
